value.0: This pedestal has pictographs describing a battle between demons, giants and the forces of good. The statues are in surprisingly good shape, but the ceiling has collapsed.

The unblinking eyes of this stature blankly return your gaze. There is no marker identifying who this figure might have been. This room is in surprisingly good condition, though as with most of the ruins, all wood and cloth has long been rotted away, the statues are not damaged and the floor and walls intact.
Crushed by the falling ceiling, this skeleton still holds a crumbling stone key in its hands.
This key is worn, barely intact. It is made of ancient stone.

The low pedestal is sandstone brown, shadows playing across its worn column. It has designs of the sun on it. This was obviously a temple to the Morninglord. Low moans are heard from the shadows as undead mingle with shadow and spirit.

The low pedestal gleams an alabaster white, shadows playing across its fluted column. Names of buried priests of Lathander are written in the stone. Broken tombs line the walls. The three circles in the room are in the pictographs. They refer to fire, air and stone.
The sarcophagus' heavy lid is fashioned from unadorned stone.
These skeletons appear to have been flattened by the ceiling. Bits of leather and other equipment have not completely rotten away. They appear to have been rogues.
This key was obviously made by a skilled rogue.
Remains of some poor Abiz cityfolk.
Remains of some poor Abiz cityfolk.
